AU  - Cavoli, Tony
AU  - Rajan, Ramkishen
AB  - This paper uses a simple stylized macro model to examine the case for
and operational mechanics behind an open inflation targeting (IT)
arrangement which has increasingly been advocated for small and open
developing economies in Asia and elsewhere. The model is calibrated to
Thailand, which was among the first Asian country to implement an IT
arrangement. The numerical investigations are aimed at comparing
conventional optimal monetary policy under commitment and discretion
and the variations of the simple fixed MPRs (i.e. versions of “Taylor
Rules”). The simple MPRs we will examine differ in how much the real
exchange rate is represented in the rule. Will the general philosophy
behind IT be suitable for small and open developing economies in Asia?
Are some rules better than others? These are some of questions we
attempt to explore in this paper.
